mTOR/rictor phosphorylates Sgk1 at Ser422 (in the hydrophobic motif) and activates it [18925875].  This phosphorylation site was not identified or quantified in dKO vs control.   \par
\b PKA directly phosphorylates Nedd4l protein. T\b0 hree Nedd4-2 residues are phosphorylated by PKA and are required for cAMP to inhibit Nedd4-2 [Snyder 15328345],  The sites [translated to mouse numbering] are S477 (IRRPRSLS*SPTVTLS),  S371 (SSRLRSCS*VTDTVAE), and T396 (TRRARSST*VTGGEEP).    \par
\b Herc4 undergoes a marked decrease in PKA dKO  (dKO/cont = 0.10)   at a basophilic site, \b0 S830 [LLKRKPS*LDDLKE].  Probable PKA site between the catalytic cleft and the E2 binding site in the HECT; likely inhibitory.  Herc4 contains a putative RanGEF that may play a role in nuclear translocation events [26801221].  \par
Short-chain ubiquitination at K270 mediates the regulated endocytosis of the aquaporin-2 water channel in collecting duct cells  [17101973]. \par
\cf2\b Itsn2\cf1  \cf2 undergoes a profound decrease \cf1\b0 in phosphorylation at a basophilic site in the PKA dKO, namely Ser491 [LSS\cf2 RKKS*\cf1 LHLELE] (dKO/cont = 0.002).  Probable obligate PKA site. This site is between the second EH domain and the first SH3 domain.\par
Itsn2 is an adapter protein that may provide an indirect link between the endocytic membrane traffic and the actin assembly machinery and may regulate the formation of clathrin-coated vesicles.  \par
Intersectins are adaptor proteins that interact with dynamin and clathrin adaptors to regulate endocytosis [10922467]. In collecting duct cells, intersectins regulate endocytosis of Kcnj1 potassium channel at apical plasma membrane [17380208] and hypothetically plays a similar  role to regulate AQP2 endocytosis. \par
Vasopressin increases the half life of AQP2 protein molecules in collecting duct cells [20724536, 24029424].  Half life increase from 10 to 14 hours in mpkCCD cells  [24029424].  \par
Vasopressin inhibits AQP2 endocytosis [12676734, 8396343].\par
\cf3\b Wnk1 \b0 S382 phosphorylation [RASFAKS*VIGTPE] is decreased in PKA dKO (PKA dKO/cont =0.40).  This site is in the activation loop and is presumably stimulatory. This suggests that PKA activation likely results in Wnk1 activation.  The effect of PKA is likely indirect since this is not a basophilic site. \par
\cf4 Two basophilic sites in \cf5\b Itpr3\cf4\b0  showed a profound decrease in phosphorylation in PKA dKO cells, viz.  S934 [VLS\cf5 RKQS\cf4 *VFGASS] and S1832 [TKG\cf5 RVSS\cf4 *FSMPSS].  The phospho-occupancy dKO/cont values were: S934, 0.005;  and S1832, 0.135.    Both sites are in the long N-terminal tail. \cf1 PKA enhances InsP\sub 3\nosupersub -induced Ca\super 2+\nosupersub  mobilization \{PMID: 9488697].\par
Phosphorylation of Itpr3 at \cf4 S934 and S1832 has been shown to be mediated by PKA \{PMID: \cf1 16107208].\par
\cf4 Vasopressin increases intracellular calcium via the vasopressin V2 receptor [2838523,     8342613] The mobilization is via an increase in the frequency of aperiodic Ca spikes [17957381, 18667481]. \par
cAMP/PKA induce ITP receptor mediated Ca oscillations in a variety of cell types (14505457).   This hypothetically may be in part due to a phosphorylation-induced  increase in Ca sensitivity of Ca-induced Ca release mechanism, increasing the likelihood that random Ca fluctuations will result in calcium release from the endoplasmic reticulum.  \par
Direct phosphorylation by protein kinase A (PKA) is indicated by thick blue lines.  These phosphorylation targets are inferred from quantitative LC-MS/MS studies in which phosphorylation changes are measured in PKA double knockout mpkCCD cells versus control cells, inferred from the published literature, or inferred by both kinds of evidence.  mpkCCD is a vasopressin-sensitive cell line from mouserenal collecting duct expressing the V2 vasopressin receptor (Avpr2) and the vasopressin-regulated water channel aquaporin-2.  Possible downstream effects indicated by black lines.  Yellow rectangles indicate known physiological responses to vasopressin in collecting duct cells. \par
\cf1 PKA activates Rap1 (via  Src) through activation of RapGEF1 [11804588]. Src phosphorylates it at Y514 (mouse).  However, no phsphosphorylation site showed any change in any RapGEF. \par
No phosphorylation changes found in Rap1a or Rap1b in PKA dKO cells versus control. Note that Rap1a and Rap1b translocate from nucleus in response to vasopressin in mpkCCD cells [22440904], increasing in the cytosolic fraction [26310817].\par
Rap1-GTP was shown to block Ras-dependent activation of Raf-1 \ul  [\ulnone 8253074].\par
Sipa1l1 showed a profound decrease in phospho-occupancy  at Ser1611 (LPLRRPS*YTLGMK) in PKA double knockout cells versus control.  This is likely to be a direct and exclusive PKA site. Sipa1l1 is a PDZ-domain containing RapGAP.  Site is downstream from the PDZ domain. Effect on activity is not known; modeled here as inhibitory. \par
\pard ERK2 (Mapk1) activation loop phosphorylation \b\fs21 (T183/Y185) was \b0\fs24 more than doubled in the PKA dKO cells versus the control cells ( dKO/cont = \b\fs21 2.18).  ERK1 (Mapk3) did not show such a change (dKO/cont = 1.36) .\par
\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\b0\fs24 In general ERK2 is activated by phosphorylation by MEK1 (Map2k1) or MEK2 (Map2k2).  However, we did not detect the activation loop phospho-peptide of Map2k1 or Map2k2.   Previous studies have shown MEK1/MEK2 phosphorylation is decreased in response to vasopressin in collecting duct cells [18667481].\par
Raf1 is activated by Ras proteins. Raf1 phosphorylation at S301 (SSPNNLS*PTGWSQ) was substantially increased in the PKA dKO (dKO/cont = 1.682).  Phosphorylation decreases activity [Kinexus PhosphoNet].  This could represent a component of a negative feedback loop that modulates the ERK2 activity decrease seen with vasopressin.  A previous study using western blotting with phospho-specific antibodies showed that vasopressin increases Raf1 phosphorylation at S259 (an inhibitory site) [18667481]. In PKA double KO cells in the present study, phosphorylation at this site [QRQRSTS*TPNVHM]was only marginally decreased (dKO /cont = 0.78) indicating that PKA may contribute marginally to the change in phosphorylation seen with vasopressin. \par
A-Raf phosphorylation at S255 (DGAPRGS*PSPASV) is markedly increased in the PKA dKO (dKO/cont = 2.170).  Phosphorylation at this site increases activity [Kinexus PhosphoNet].  Thus, we would expect to have decreased activity in response to vasopressin, which could help to drive the decrease in ERK2 activation.  This is a proline directed site and thus potentially a JNK target as assumed in the model.    \par
\pard\b Map3k5 is a MAP kinase kinase kinase, also known as \b0\i Apoptosis signal regulated kinase 1 \i0 (\b ASK1\b0 ).  Phosphorylation at \b  Ser\b0 973 [EYLRSIS*LPVPVL] was decreased in the PKA dKO\b  (dKO/cont = \cf2  0.51\cf1 ).  This is a basophilic site consistent with PKA target creating a 14-3-3 protein binding site (RSxS*xP) and suppression of enzyme activity (Kinexus PhosphoNet). \par
 \b0\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1 Map2k7 shows moderate increase at Ser293 (dKO/cont = 1.33) and Ser73 (dKO/cont = 1.76).  Serine293 is a potential activating site in the activation loop (SKAKTRS*AGCAAY), although primary site is listed as Thr291.  Effect of Ser73 phosphorylation not documented in Kinexus PhosphoNet. Map2k7 is JNK kinase 2 and activates JNK and not p38.                             \cf4\par
\cf1 No JNK phosphopeptides were found in PKA dKO cells.  However, its canonical target, the transcription factor \b Jun\b0 , showed a marked increase in phosphorylation at Ser63 (dKO/cont = 3.44) in the PKA dKO cells. (This is adjacent to the site that is strongly downregulated in response to vasopressin, viz. Ser73, also a JNK site).\par
Large-scale quantitative phosphoprotoemics studies in mouse mpkCCD collecting duct cells [20139300] and native rat IMCD cells from kidney [20075062] have demonstrated that vasopressin, working through the V2 vasopressin receptor and cAMP results in a wide ranging decrease in phosphorylation of proteins at sites with proline in position +1 relative to the phosphorylated S or T.  The results imply that vasopressin signaling is associated with a decrease in activation of one or more proline-directed kinases, i.e. MAP kinases or cyclin-dependent kinases. \par
Ras isoforms are activated by epidermal growth factor [12054111], resulting in activation of the MAP kinase pathway in collecting duct cells  [8092250, 18667481]. This is believed to occure through Raf1 activation [1312393, 12054111].  Epidermal growth factor inhibits the ability of vasopressin to increase water permeability in the renal collecting duct [2844852].\par
\cf2\b Protein Kinase D1 (Prkd1) \cf3 is an AGC family kinase also known as Protein kinase C mu and is regulated in part by diacylglycerol (DAG). \cf2  It \cf3 undergoes a large increase in phosphorylation at S403 [DSNRTIS*PSTSNN] in the PKA double KO cells (dKO/cont = 3.76). This is a proline-directed site, likely phosphorylated by a MAP kinase. When phosphorylated, it binds 14-3-3 regulating its localization in the cell and reducing activity at membrane surfaces (Kinexus PhosphoNet). Decreased phosphorylation in response to PKA therefore activates it. \par
\par
S511 in Pi4kb showed a marked decrease in phospho-occupancy in the PKA double KO cells (dKO/cont = 0.05).  This site is likely an exclusive direct PKA site (DIRRRLS*EQLAHT).   This is located just upstream of the catalytic domain, but the physiological effect was not reported (Kinexus PhosphoNet). The protein kinase D1 site, S294, was not identified and therefore not quentified in the PKA double KO cells. The hypothetical tryptic peptide is 6 amino acids.\par
\par
Protein kinase D (PKD) is recruited to the trans-Golgi network (TGN) and is required for the biogenesis of TGN to cell surface transport carriers [\cf1\b0 18086912]\cf3\b .  In the trans-Golgi network (TGN), it regulates fission of transport vesicles that mediate trafficking to the plasma membrane [\cf1\b0 18086912]\cf3\b .  The effect seems to mediated by phosphorylation and activation of phosphatidylinositol 4-kinaseIII\u946? (PI4KIII\u946?) (\cf1\b0 16100512\cf3\b ).  \cf4\b0\par
\pard I\f1 n M1 cortical collecting duct cells\f0 , aldosterone mediated ENaC trafficking from the TGN to plasma membrane occurred via protein kinase D1-phosphatidylinositol 4-kinaseIII\f1\'e2 \f0 TGN \f1 signalling \f0 [\cf3\b 23541637].  Deletion of a Pi4kb interacting protein Plekha8 (FAPP2) inhibits TGN to apical plasma membrane translocation of AQP2 [19794145].\par
\par
Vasopressin, via the V2 receptor, increases the rate of exocytic insertion of AQP2 into the apical plasma membrane in collecting duct cells [18799651, 8396343, 12676734].  (Note: Many studies have demonstrated vasopressin-induced redistribution of AQP2 to the apical domain in collecting duct cells but do not distinguish between effects of exo- versus endocytosis.)\par
\par
The phosphorylation of calmodulin at Y100 was decreased in the PKA dKO cells versus control (dKO/cont = 0.53).  This site is a target for both EGFR and non-receptor kinases including Src and Fyn [10411641].  Phosphorylation of Y100 on CaM generally increases its affinity for regulatory target proteins, increasing their activation [10411641].  \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf4\b0\par
Binding of calmodulin to Camk2 and Camk2 isoforms results in conformational change that relieves intrasteric autoinhibition.\par
Camk2b and Camk2d are both very abundant in collecting duct cells.  They are basophilic kinases with target specificity similar to Protein Kinase A.  \par
Recombinant CAMK2 phosphorylated AQP2 at Ser256 in vitro [24598363].  Target sequence:  REVRRRQS*VELHSPQ.  Large-scale data integration ranking protein kinases with regard to likelihood of phosphorylating AQP2 at Ser256 identified CAMK2 as the top-ranked kinase in mpkCCD cells [26310817] and native rat renal inner medullary collecting duct cells [24598363].\par
\par
Ser256 phosphorylation in AQP2 is sustained in mpkCCD cells after PKA double KO. \par
Ser256 phosphorylation in AQP2 has been seen to increase in response to vasopressin in some studies [9950956,16641100], but this response has not been seen in other studies [19190182, 20089674].  Xie et al. quantified phospho-occupancy at Ser256 in rat innner medullary collecting duct, showing that the baseline level of Ser256 phosphorylation was constitutively high, and there was no increase with vaspressin [20089674].   Phosphorylation of Ser256 of AQP2 is a pre-requisite for phosphorylation at Ser264 and Ser269, but increases at Ser264 and Ser269 do not depend on an increase at Ser256 [18606813].  Phosphorylation at Ser256 is thought to be necessary for  AQP2 exocytosis [9227644].\par
Ser269 phosphorylation in AQP2 has been seen to increase many fold in response to vasopressin in collecting duct cells [18606813,20089674].  Phosphorylation of this site was undectable in mpkCCD cells when both PKA catalytic subunit genes were deleted, indicating that Ser269 phosphorylation requires PKA, presumably because it is a direct substrate. \par
Ser261 is the only site in AQP2 that decreases in response to vasopressin[18606813,20089674].  Phosphorylation of this site was increased in mpkCCD cells when both PKA catalytic subunit genes were deleted, indicating that Ser261 phosphorylation is negatively regulated by PKA.  This site has a proline in position +1 and is a likely substrate of one or mre proline-directed kinases. Interestingly, in the PKA double KO cells, vasopressin increased phosphorylation, suggesting a PKA-independent phosphorylation event that is normally masked by the PKA-dependent decrease in phosphorylation. This vasopressin response could have been a result of direct cAMP-mediated regulation of RapGEF3 (EPAC1) or RapGEF4 (EPAC2), activation of arrestin-mediated MAPK pathway activation, or a G-(beta/gamma) effect. \par
\par
Ser264 phosphorylation in AQP2 has been seen to increase in response to vasopressin in collecting duct cells [18606813,20089674].  Phosphorylation of this site was sustained in mpkCCD cells when both PKA catalytic subunit genes were deleted, indicating that some other unknown protein kinase phosphorylates it.  Its investigation is hindered by very low phospho-occupancy (<5%) even in the presence of vasopressin [] so we cannot rule out the possibility that PKA can phosphorylate it. \par
\cf3\par
Theoretically, S269 phosphorylation could interfere with K270 ubiqutylation. However, S269 phosphorylation and K270 ubiquitylation do not appear to be mutually exclsusive [24876223].   Although K63-linked polyubiquitylation marks AQP2 for endocytosis, site-specific phosphorylation can over-ride polyubiquitylation to determine the localization of the AQP2 water channel [24876223].  \par
S269 phosphorylation potentiates plasma membrane retention of AQP2, presumably by inhibiting endocytosis [18606813]. Theoretically, this could occur if S269 phosphorylation interferes with K270 ubiqutylation. However, S269 phosphorylation and K270 ubiquitylation do not appear to be mutually exclsusive [24876223]. Although K63-linked polyubiquitylation marks AQP2 for endocytosis, site-specific phosphorylation can over-ride polyubiquitylation to determine the localization of the AQP2 water channel [24876223].\par
