\pard\cf0\kerning0\f2\fs22 Dear Karl -\par
\~\par
On my paper with Brad Yu on the mechanism of AQP2 endocytosis and its regulation by vasopressin (JASN-2016-06-0601.R1), we were seemingly done in by a single rogue referee.\~ The reviewer criticisms were largely about new questions posed by the referee and\~ not posed by us.\~\~\par
\par
 I think that the job of the referee is to address whether the question(s) raised\~ by the authors have been answered and whether the answers justify the conclusions (and of course whether the questions asked are important enough to move the field).\~ I do not think it is fair for the referee to pose his/her own questions.\~ Consequently, I am requesting reconsideration of the journal's decision.\~ One thing that could be done is to ask the other two (seemingly positive) reviewers for feedback. \par
\par
 If necessary we can provide responses to the comments, but, for brevity's sake, I have not provided them here.\par
\~\par
I believe that the paper addressed an important mystery about how Ser269 phosphorylation of aquaporin-2 regulates aquaporin-2 endocytosis, providing the mechanistic information needed to understand diabetes insipidus syndromes. \par
\~\par
The review correspondence is included in the thread below.\~ \par
\~\par
Let me know your thoughts on this.\par
\~\par
Mark\par
\~\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf3\kerning24\b\f0\fs24 Bad interacts with death repressor protein Bcl-X(L) in mitochondrial outer membrane reversing its death repressor activity   ... Promotes cell death.  Phosphorylated on Ser-155, blocking its pro-apoptotic activity.\b0    Thus, PKA activation and Bad phosphorylation is predicted to inhibit apoptosis and promote survival.  \b Appears to act as a link between growth factor receptor signaling and the apoptotic pathways. \par
\pard\cf5 Ser155 of Bad is a classic PKA target (PhosphoSitePlus). [PMID: 10880354].\par
\par
In the PKA double KO cells, there was a marked decrease in phosphorylation at S155 [RELRRMS*DEFEGS]  (dKO/cont=0.12) . \par
\par
\cf1 Bad interacts with death repressor protein Bcl-X(L) in mitochondrial outer membrane reversing its death repressor activity. Therefore it is pro-apoptotic.  \par
Phosphorylation on Ser-155 by PKA, blocks its pro-apoptotic activity.\b0    \par
\par
Thus, PKA activation and Bad phosphorylation at Ser155 are predicted to inhibit apoptosis and promote survival.  \par
Vasopressin inhibits apoptosis in renal collecting duct cells through the V2 receptor and downstream cAMP-mediated pathways in mammalian kidney [23136001].\par
\par
 Vasopressin increases phosphorylation of Bad at S155 in collecting duct cells  [23136001]. \par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf3\b\par
\pard\cf5 Bim (\cf1\b0 Bcl2l11), which is pro-apoptotic, undergoes an increase in phosphorylation in the PKA dKO at S73 [GPFATRS*PLFIFV], a proline directed site (dKO/cont = 1.64).   Bim is expressed in various splicing variant forms and is subject to multisite phosphorylation at proline-directed sites by both ERK and JNK [15947788].  At least some of these phosphorylation events enhance apoptosis (e.g. at Ser65 of mouse) although the Ser73  site found lacks documentation. Ser65 phosphorylation was  only identified in one PKA dKO/control pair and the dKO/cont ratio was 1000. \par
\par
Decreased Bim phosphorylation by Jnk1 with PKA activation predicts a decrease in apoptotic rate. \par
\par
\cf3\b The Fgd proteins are CDC42-specific GEFs called \ldblquote FYVE, RhoGEF and PH domain-containing proteins\rdblquote .  Via the FYVE domain, they selectively bind  phosphatidylinositol 3- phosphate [\cf1\ul\b0 9697764\ulnone ], which localizes them to early endosomes and plasma membrane (Cf. EEA1). They are involved in coupling the actin cytoskeleton to the plasma membrane [18410521].   \cf3\b Fgd3 underwent a profound decrease in phosphoryation at Ser442 [ITGRKRS*LELQTR], a strong basophilic site and likely PKA direct target (dKO/cont = 0.02).   The site is amid the first PH domain, upstream from the FYVE domain.  No data on effect of phosphorylation.  It is proposed to inhibit binding to membrane and therefore to limit activity at apical plasma membrane.  \cf5\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf3\par
Also, Fgd1 underwent a marked increase in phosphorylation at Ser116 [ILVKSLS*LDPGQS], a canonical 14-3-3 target, which may sequester it. (dKO/cont = 3.17). This site is not depicted in model. \par
CDC42-specific GEFs catalyze exchange of GDP for GTP, thereby activating CDC42. \par
\pard\cf2 CDC42 \cf3 is a small GTP-binding protein that is attached to lipid bilayers via a geranylgeranyl anchor at the C-terminus.  Classically,\cf1\b0   CDC42, Rac, and Rho play different roles in different membrane domains.   In the context of cell migration, CDC42, Rac, and Rho regulate filopodia, lamellipodia, and stress fibers respectively\cf3\b  [Hall, Science, 1998: \cf1\b0 9438836]. \par
\par
\cf3\b E\cf2 ffectors for CDC42 \cf3 in nucleation of plasma membrane associated actin polymerization  are the \cf2 Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome proteins\cf3 , Was and Wasl.  Wasl is the most abundant in mpkCCD cells, although Was could also play role. Neither were found to undergo phosphorylation changes in the PKA double KO. Was and Wasl have N-terminal CRIB domains that bind CDC42\par
\par
Wasl and Was interact with the Arp2/3 complex to drive actin filament nucleation and branching.  \cf1 The resulting actin polymerization can drive membrane movement, e.g. in lamellipodia. Although phosphorylation sites were detected in some of the subunits of the Arp2/3 complex, none were altered in phospho-occupancy in the PKA dKO.  This process has been seen to drive membrane invagination in endocytosis [\b0 25143395\b ].\par
\par
\b0 Pacsins are \cf2\b F-Bar domain proteins \cf1\b0 that bend the lipid bilayer (e.g. membrane tubulation) and bind dynamin.  They regulate internalization of plasma membrane proteins such as GLUT1 and TRPV4 [UniProt].  They bind WASP via their Src homology 3 domains at COOH-terminus. PACSIN proteins colocalize with \cf2\b dynamin\cf1\b0  [11082044]. \par
Pacsin3 at Ser319 [KEKGGRS*PDEVTL] undergoes an increase in phosphorylation in the PKA dKO (dKO/cont = 1.68), a proline-directed site upstream from SH3 domain. \par
\par
As described in endocytic actin patches in fission yeast [25143395], the polymerization  may provide a motive force for membrane invagination, aided by one or more F-BAR proteins (Pacsins, Trip10) that bend the lipid bilayer and bind dynamin. The movement of endocytic vesicles, once pinched off probably does not depend on actin polymerization [25143395].\par
\cf3\b\par
This database reports proteins identified by yeast-two-hybrid (Y2H) that bind to UT-A1 C-terminal fragment. The data are from studies carried out in the laboratory of Dr. Guangping Chen at Emory University [Xu G, Su H, Carter CB, Fr\'f6hlich O, Chen G. Depolymerization of cortical actin inhibits UT-A1 urea transporter endocytosis but promotes forskolin-stimulated membrane trafficking. Am J Physiol Cell Physiol. 2012; 302:C1012-8. PMID: 22262062]. Also reported are the relative expression levels in the three renal tubule segments known to express UT-A1 (Slc14a2) from a study by Lee et al. [Lee JW, Chou CL, Knepper MA. Deep Sequencing in Microdissected Renal Tubules Identifies Nephron Segment-Specific Transcriptomes. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2015; 26:2669-77. PMID: 25817355]. The interacting proteins from yeast two-hybrid studies are considered more likely to interact with UT-A1 isoforms in vivo if they are expressed in the same cells as UT-A1.\par
