\pard\cf5\b Nfatc2\cf1  undergoes marked dephosphorylation at Ser237 [GAK\cf2 RRHS\cf1 *CAEALV] in PKA double KO (dKO/cont =\cf5  0.27). \cf1 This site is a likely direct PKA site.  This site overlaps the nuclear localization sequence and may regulate this TF by affecting localization.  This may be opposed in part by activation of the phosphatase calcineurin (\b0 Ppp3ca (PP2-B)\b ).  There are several phosphorylation sites in Nfatc2 that are targets of calcineurin in the 99-365 region [11030334]. Upon cell stimulation, all these\par
sites except Ser-245 are dephosphorylated by calcineurin. These would be predicted to show an increase in phosphorylation in the PKA dKO. Indeed, some sites showed marked increases in PKA dKO:  Ser99 (dKO/cont = 251), Ser270 (dKO/cont = 27), Ser748 (dKO/cont = 105).  Others showed no change: Ser136, Ser150, Ser219, Ser223.  UniProt: \b0 Rapid nuclear exit of NFATC is thought to be one mechanism by which cells distinguish between sustained and transient calcium signals. Nfatc2 is a member of the multicomponent NFATC transcription complex that consists of  NFATC2,  NFATC1, AP1, MAF, GATA isoforms and Crebbp. \b\par
\par
\b0 An Nfat enhancer element is located 489 bp upstream of the AQP2 transcription start site influences hypertonicity-stimulated AQP2 transcriptional activity [16641150]. Nfatc regulates AQP2 gene expression and functional NFAT binding sites within the proximal AQP2 promoter [bp]  are responsible for regulation of AQP2 by NFATc proteins [17166937].  \b\par
\par
UniProt: \b0 Cytoplasmic for the phosphorylated form and nuclear after activation\'85 phosphorylation is controlled in part by calcineurin-mediated dephosphorylation. Rapid nuclear exit of NFATC is thought to be one mechanism by which cells distinguish between sustained and transient calcium signals. The subcellular localization of NFATC plays a key role in the regulation of gene transcription. Nfatc regulates AQP2 gene expression and functional NFAT binding sites within the proximal AQP2 promoter [bp]  are responsible for regulation of AQP2 by NFATc proteins [17166937].  An Nfat enhancer element located 489 bp upstream of the AQP2 transcription start site influences hypertonic stimulation of AQP2 transcriptional activity [16641150].  Nfatc2 is a member of the multicomponent NFATC transcription complex that consists of at least two components, a pre-existing cytoplasmic component NFATC2 and an inducible nuclear component NFATC1. Other members the complex: AP1 TFs, MAF, GATA isoforms and Crebbp. The phosphorylated form specifically interacts with XPO1; which mediates nuclear export. \b\par
\pard\sa200\sl276\slmult1\cf5 Nfatc2\cf1   is regulated in part by activation of the phosphatase calcineurin (\b0 Ppp3ca (PP2-B)\b ) through calmodulin activation in association with cytoplasmic calcium mobilization.  There are several such phosphorylation sites in Nfatc2 that are targets of calcineurin. \b0 NFAT1 is phosphorylated on fourteen conserved phosphoserine residues in its regulatory domain, thirteen of which are dephosphorylated upon stimulation. Dephosphorylation of all thirteen residues is required to mask a nuclear export signal (NES), cause full exposure of a nuclear localization signal (NLS), and promote transcriptional activity\b  \b0\par
